{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:52:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.62,0.05,0.17,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7060"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"898"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4615"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman is admitted to the general medical ward from the Emergency Department (ED) with community-acquired pneumonia. She has a medical history of congestive heart failure, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and a previous myocardial infarction. Her regular medications include metformin, ramipril, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShortly after arrival to the ward, an emergency call is made due to sudden onset of tachypnoea. On examination, she appears unwell with a respiratory rate of 34/min. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/55 mmHg, SpO2 94% on supplemental oxygen (initially 88% on room air), and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral crepitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReview of her chart shows that in ED she received ceftriaxone and azithromycin within the past hour, in addition to one litre of intravenous fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glyceryl trinitrate","Furosemide","Morphine","Adrenaline","Escalation of antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute pulmonary oedema complicating her pneumonia. The most appropriate next step in management is therefore administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Efurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E. Furosemide is a loop diuretic that rapidly reduces preload by increasing venous capacitance and promoting diuresis. In this case, the patient\u0027s underlying congestive heart failure, combined with the inflammatory response to pneumonia and the recent fluid administration, has likely precipitated acute pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscalation of antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate at this stage. The patient has only recently received appropriate antibiotic therapy for community-acquired pneumonia, and there is insufficient time to assess its efficacy. The acute deterioration is more likely due to fluid overload rather than worsening infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphine\u003C/strong\u003E has traditionally been used in acute pulmonary oedema for its anxiolytic and venodilatory effects. However, its use is controversial due to potential respiratory depression, and it is not recommended as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlyceryl trinitrate (GTN)\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in acute pulmonary oedema, particularly if associated with hypertension or ischaemia, as it reduces preload through venodilation. However with this patient\u0027s borderline blood pressure and the likely aetiology of fluid overload, furosemide would be the preferred initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be the treatment of choice for anaphylaxis. Whilst the patient has recently been administered antibiotics which are a common allergen, she does not have other typical features of anaphylaxis such as urticaria, angioedema, or hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of acute pulmonary oedema follows a stepwise approach: First, ensure adequate oxygenation with supplemental oxygen targeting SpO2 92-96%. Consider non-invasive ventilation if respiratory distress persists despite oxygen therapy. Administer intravenous furosemide (40-80mg) as first-line treatment. In hypertensive patients, consider nitrates. Position the patient upright unless hypotensive. Monitor response to treatment through clinical parameters, fluid balance, and serial chest x-rays. Address underlying causes and review fluid status carefully.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute pulmonary oedema can complicate pneumonia, especially in patients with pre-existing heart failure.","Furosemide is the first-line treatment for acute pulmonary oedema in the context of fluid overload.","Careful fluid management is crucial in patients with both pneumonia and heart failure."],"references":["Purvey M, Allen G. Managing acute pulmonary oedema. Aust Prescr. 2017 Apr;40(2):59-63. doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2017.012. Epub 2017 Apr 3. PMID: 28507398; PMCID: PMC5408000. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5408000/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:24:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:30:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7060"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87128"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu